t-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">All involved should be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ashamed</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. Their malpractice could not be clearer – I never made one error of fact or process in five years of complaints about this malpractice</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> but</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> I was denied, misdirected, ignored, and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">mishcaracterized</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> I’ll never get justice and nobody will ever be hel</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">d accountable. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">All I have achieved are apologies for miscommunication from every authority.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Until these authorities are changed, health workers never will be accountable and we will continue to suffer </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">routine</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ly</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">unacceptabl</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> care and abuses of power by hea</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">lth workers.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">RECOMMENDATIONS: </span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Stop self-regulation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. All the so-called professional regulators are self-regulators – they take public money, but they appoint their own regulators from within their own professions. This is incestuous. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In some cases, they are investigating their friends or even themselves (for instance, as Lynda Deacon warned, she sat on the same council that was charged with investigating her; it promoted her). </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The regulators should be professional civil servants outsid</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e of the profession that they are regulating.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Bring the QUANGOs back within government</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. Government has pushed health care regulation out to quasi-non-governmental organizations (QUANGOs) that take public money but are not accountable to government, to the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">benefit of both sides, but not the public. Government can deny responsibility when health care goes wrong, QUANGOs can avoid accountability. If government is providing public health care, government should be regulating public health care</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> directly, not thr</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ough QUANGOs</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Persons should be held accountable</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. At the moment, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">when someone complains of the failures of an organization like the HCPC, only the organization is investigated. T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">he Ombudsman investigates only 1% of received complaints; even if </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">it were</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nvestigate, it refuses to investigate persons, only organizations. Consequently, the worst that an organization can expect is a ruling that “mistakes were made” and that it should apologize and perhaps compensate, but no particular person is ever named as </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">responsible. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">A single person should be responsible for all correspondence from the complainant to the organization</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. In my experience, every time I contacted </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">any of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">these authorities I was complaining to an impersonal </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">webportal</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> or email address with no nam</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ed responsible party. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">f I received a reply from any person, this person would </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">have</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">different </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">name</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to the last person</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. This practice allows for unaccountability and dropped correspondence </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and is practically impossible to investigate forensically</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Strengt</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">hen civil law</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. Britain has a weak tort system that discourages frivolous actions by disallowing actions outside of a few months of the injustice and by awarding damages in only the most egregious cases. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Yet regulators can frustrate complaints for years. </span><span style="font-